&lt;p&gt;Stratton-Berkessel quotes Felix Adler who said &amp;ldquo;To care for anyone else enough to make their problems one&amp;rsquo;s own, is ever the beginning of one&amp;rsquo;s real ethical development.&amp;rsquo;&amp;rsquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Jaqueline Kelm in chapter 3 of her book &amp;ldquo;Appreciative Living,&amp;rdquo; describes Appreciative Inquiry&amp;rsquo;s Simultaneity Principle. She writes, &amp;ldquo;The internal and external questions we ask steer our thinking, attention, and images in one direction or another, which in turn directs our decisions and creates our experience. There is a saying that goes something like, &amp;ldquo;If you keep doing what you always did, you&amp;rsquo;ll keep getting what you always got.&amp;rdquo; In the same vein, if we continue to ask the same questions, we&amp;rsquo;ll continue to create the same world. We have patterns of thinking that tend to lead us down similar questioning paths.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kelm goes on to discuss all the questions we face upon waking each morning such as whether to hit the snooze button on the alarm or what to wear for the day. She writes, &amp;ldquo;...each of our choices was an answer to an implicit question. For example, our decision about what to eat for breakfast came from an internal question that might have been, &amp;ldquo;What do I feel like eating today?&amp;rdquo; Or perhaps it was, &amp;ldquo;What&amp;rsquo;s in the kitchen I can eat quickly for breakfast today?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kelm continues, &amp;ldquo;Consider what would happen if we asked one different question in the morning such as, &amp;ldquo;What would be the healthiest thing I could eat this morning that would leave me feeling good about myself and give me the greatest energy to start the day?&amp;rdquo; Even if we made the same breakfast choice, it would be done with a different mindset. If we continued to ask this same new question each morning, at some point we would begin to change our actions by virtue of our attention&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With the Simultaneity Principle in mind,&amp;nbsp; What are three things you are grateful for?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Considering that whatever we focus on begins to grow. Are there moments from the last few days that you want more of?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, would you like to be eating more healthy foods? You could be grateful for a particularly healthy meal you had recently.&amp;nbsp; If you would like to get more fit, you could be grateful for that flight of stairs you climbed the other day.&amp;nbsp; If you want better relationships, perhaps you could recall a recent conversation with a loved one and be grateful for it!&lt;/p&gt;

